s in the United States is the first book to provide a comprehensive and lively analysis of the contributions of artists from America's newest immigrant communities--Africa, the Middle East, China, India, Southeast Asia, Central America, and Mexico. Adding significantly to our understanding of both the arts and immigration, multidisciplinary scholars explore tensions that artists face in forging careers in a new world and navigating between their home communities and the larger society. They address the art forms that these modern settlers bring with them; show how poets, musicians, playwrights, and visual artists adapt traditional forms to new environments; and consider the ways in which the communities' young people integrate their own traditions and concerns into contemporary expression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArts and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aArts and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocial life and customsy20th century. 0aImmigrantszUnited StatesxSocial life and customsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCárdenas, Gilberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCârdenas, Gilberto.1 aDiMaggio, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiMaggio, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDurand, Jorge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspiritu, Yen Le, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspiritu, Yen Le.1 aFernandez-Kelly, Patricia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFernandez-Kelly, Patricia.1 aFernández-Kelly, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJamal, Amaney, econtributor.4ctb4htt